story:
After such a difficult year for everyone, let`s have some fun, get into the Christmas spirit and raise some money for Macmillan Cancer Support.

Sky Betting and Gaming and Macmillan Cancer Support are working together to support more people living with and affected by cancer. The statistics:1 in 2 people in the UK will get a cancer diagnosis in their lifetime. 1000 people will get diagnosed each day in the UK3 million people are living with cancer in the UK today Macmillan`s ambition is to be there for every person living with cancer and provide them with tailored support when they need it most. Being told you have cancer is life-changing, and having the right support can have a huge impact physically, financially and emotionally. The number of people living with cancer today is nearly 3 million, and this is set to rise to over 5 million by 2040. Sky Betting and Gaming`s support is needed more than ever.

story:
In memory of our dear colleague, Donna Matta, who has passed away following a short illness.   Many of you will have known Donna, who was an OSC Coordinator in Stevenage, and will remember her commitment to the Company and team.  Her kind and generous nature will be greatly missed. 

We extend our deepest sympathy to her family at this time, as Donna's sudden passing will be a tremendous loss to them.

Your kind donation in Donna's memory will help those suffering from Cancer and enable them to get the support they need.

26 LETTERS 🐾 26 DAYS 🐾 26 PHOTOS 

I will be posting a photo each day for the next 26 days of Ted with something (or somewhere) beginning with each letter of the alphabet as part of the AlphaPET Challenge. Anyone who knows Ted, will know he loves the camera. 

Macmillan is such an amazing organisation which provides support for so many people; one charity very close to my heart. A few fun, creative photos is the least I can do to show my appreciation and support to such a wonderful charity. So I hope you jump on board and support Ted and I to support Macmillan. No matter how big or small the donation is, every penny counts. 

Linsey & Ted 🐾💚

story:
In May 2018 I had 13 inches of hair cut off and donated to the Little Princess Trust, this hair was used to create a much needed wig for a child in need. All of my sponsorship for having my hair cut went to Click Sargent, Macmillan and Cancer Research UK.

In December 2018 I discovered I had Bowel Cancer. After surgery and months of chemotherapy I was finally given the all clear in March 2020. During this time I was lucky enough to have had the support of my family so I did not have to call on the services of Macmillan, however some people are not so lucky. 

The COVID-19 pandemic has halted the amount of donations that would have been received through fund raising for many charities this year. So I have therefore decided to Brave the Shave to raise funds for Macmillan Cancer Support as this is one of the charities close to my heart. 

I would be extremely grateful for any donation, however big or small during these tough times we are facing. 

I thank you in advance for your donations and support. I wish you all good health. Please stay safe. 

Debbie Elson.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
When my close friend Ali was diagnosed with breast cancer in October 2020 - with COVID and an impending national lockdown making it hard to offer practical, hands-on support - I wanted to find another way to help.


My last fundraising effort was a sponsored silence at primary school (which I probably failed!), and anyone who knows me well will also know I'm no athlete.  Undeterred by this, I've set myself a virtual cycling challenge on the Peloton spin bike in aid of Macmillan Cancer Support.  During November and December, I aim to cycle the xxx-mile return distance from Ali's home in Wimbledon to her childhood home in Yorkshire.

Any amount you're able to donate will be hugely appreciated and gladly received by Macmillan.  £25 will support an hour on their phone support line and £50 can ensure a Macmillan nurse is there when someone is diagnosed with cancer.  Thank you in advance.

"Whatever cancer throws your way, we're right there with you" - Macmillan Cancer Support

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Cancer remains one of the 'big five' in the UK and with more than 367k new cases every year it is something that we have all been affected by in one way or another.

Research is coming on and survivability is on the up, however the battle is not solely physiological - it has social, emotional and practical impacts, for both patients themselves, and their family/friends.

In a year when normal fundraising activities are all but impossible, we're brushing off the old console/controllers and 'going to war' for 24 hours, in support of those who support cancer patients from diagnosis onwards in their own battles.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

We thank you in advance for your generosity when contributing to Ronald's memorial page. The British Heart Foundation is doing incredible things but the research can not continue without lovely people like you taking the time and effort to donate.

Ronald was quite a character and was forever telling us all funny stories about his misspent youth, adding some inappropriate comments to add shock value! He was a real entertainer and a good sport when he was the ’butt of the joke’ . 
Ronald was a doting husband to his late wife Mary, as well as a dad and grandad. He also had a fond love for the races and the blues (best team in the midlands 😉) He sadly passed away on 27/10/2020.  We want to raise as much money as we can so  if you are able to  donate anything, even in these tough times we’re in, we would really appreciate it. 

Once again we thank you. The SHEASBY’S 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. Thanks!

story:
In May 2021, I will be taking on the huge challenge of running the London Landmarks Half Marathon for the second time.  Last time I run it for a charity that was close to mine and Chris heart.  This time I’m running in memory of my father in law.  I entered the ballot shortly after Steve had sadly passed away and I knew if I was successful that I would be running for British Heart Foundation.  I found out the day before we said our final goodbyes and knew it was meant be.

Steve this one is for you ❤️. 

The last year has been an unprecedented and incredibly challenging year for the charity sector and the impact of Covid-19 has meant many charities are now struggling to raise the vital income they need to survive. Your support this year is more important than ever so thank you so much in advance for donating whatever you can. It really will make a massive difference.

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
eventName: Caerphilly and Pontypridd 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas
story:
The 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas Collection 

Help us as we aim to raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs 
this Christmas! 

During December the four-legged volunteers of the Caerphilly and Pontypridd Fundraising Group would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at collections and events in your community.  

Due to the current situation, we’re not able to be out as much this 
festive season, and we know you will miss seeing our life-changing doggy volunteers! We’re hoping you will help us and donate to our ‘12 Guide Dogs of Christmas’ Collection as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships!  

It costs over £56,000 to fund the lifetime cost of a guide dog. Please consider donating £12 during our 12-day collection so we can fund 12 new life-changers this Christmas.  

We appreciate that times are difficult, but for people with sight loss, 
social isolation can be their everyday. You can help them feel less alone, now and in the future. 

Don’t forget to send it on through Facebook, WhatsApp, email or text and get your friends and family involved too. 

Thank you and Merry Christmas!
title: Caerphilly and Pontypridd 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas

eventName: Lostwithiel & District 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas
story:
The 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas Collection

Help us as we aim to raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs
this Christmas!

During December the four-legged volunteers of the Lostwithiel & District Fundraising Group would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at collections and events in your community. 

Due to the current situation, we’re not able to be out as much this
festive season, and we know you will miss seeing our life-changing doggy volunteers! We’re hoping you will help us and donate to our ‘12 Guide Dogs of Christmas’ Collection as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships! 

It costs over £56,000 to fund the lifetime cost of a guide dog. Please consider donating £12 during our 12-day collection so we can fund 12 new life-changers this Christmas. 

We appreciate that times are difficult, but for people with sight loss,
social isolation can be their everyday. You can help them feel less alone, now and in the future.

Don’t forget to send it on through Facebook, WhatsApp, email or text and get your friends and family involved too.

Thank you and Merry Christmas!

story:
I have decided to run between my front and back door 100 times (so 50 rounds trips). This is no usual door situation, as the doors are actually part of the access to my flat and the offices behind it, so the distance between them is between 0.01 and 0.03 miles (depending on the reliability of my Fitbit). Once I hit £100, I will do the run in one go that day (or the next day if I have already been for a run that day), so if you want me to run in the pouring rain, time your donation well!

I am privileged to know several guide dogs (and their owners) and they are brilliant. I've worn glasses for over half my life but I could not imagine being unable to see - when people experience sight loss, guide dogs can help people stay connected to friends and family. Guide Dogs also does a lot more than just train dogs, and that support is really valuable. 

100 for Guide Dogs is your challenge, your way. You can choose to Run100, Cycle100 or Swim100 between 1 July and 30 November. However you take on your 100, get sponsored to do it and help us supporting people living with sight loss. You could complete 100 metres, 100 minutes, 100 days be creative! The sponsorship money you raise will make a difference. £100 could pay for five hours' training at a Guide Dogs training school.It's thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services, like our guide dogs, to people with sight loss. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge! #TeamGuideDogs

story:
In memory of our gorgeous Barty who we sadly lost on Monday, I'm going to sell these keyrings to raise money for guide dogs. Bart was the best guide dog ever and the bestest friend and poochy we could have ever asked for! He will be greatly missed everyday! 😢

If anyone would like to purchase one in memory of Bart please comment or message me below. Can be personalised with your name on the back if you would like.

£5 each or a donation with all proceeds going to the guide dogs charity. 💙


Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

story:
Every child should have the chance to be at home with their families for Christmas Day.

Your donation to GOSH Charity can make a huge difference helping to fund vital resources that GOSH needs to get seriously ill children back home as quickly as possible.

For those children whose treatment needs to continue over the festive season, your support can help bring Christmas to the hospital and make it feel like a home from home.

You can also leave a kind message of Christmas cheer below that will be shared with the children, their families and hospital staff. See the video below also to see some of the lovely messages the hospital has already received.

Help families at GOSH with the gift of your support this Christmas.

story:
Great Ormond Street Hospital relies on charitable support to go above and beyond, to provide the extraordinary care, expertise and facilities that gives children from across the UK the best chance to fulfil their potential. 

My best friend Emily has recently witnessed first hand their amazing support with her daughter Gigi’s care in the past year. To help her say a huge thank you to GOSH I am joining her to complete ‘Running Christmas Off!’ running, 31 miles in January. 

I will need to dust of my trainers (the last time I ran was a 10k with my sister back in 2010!) so if able, please kindly give whatever you can to support the wonderful GOSH. Thank you so much for supporting Team Gigi and friends 🙌🏼💕👟

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
This January, I’ll be burning off the mince pies and kicking off a healthy 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month whatever the weather to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). GOSH is an incredibly special place with amazing facilities for the families and children that visit or stay there. This fundraising effort is in support of an incredible team of professionals who have given so much to a very special little girl, Gigi. We all hope that our children will never need the services that GOSH offer, but in the event that they do we know they’ll be in the best possible hands. Your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's often life saving work will keep me going when I need it most. It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button! GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever. Thank you 😊

I’ll keep you updated with sweaty selfies and hopefully some beautiful Devon scenery along the way!

story:
I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in the ‘Running off Christmas’ January challenge. January is a bleak and gloomy month at the best of times, so I plan to turn this around and do some good for a truly worthy cause,  Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). 

I plan to represent each day of the month by running 31 miles, but this figure is purely a minimum target to achieve; I want to plough on through the pain and run many more miles! This will be completed throughout the month to raise money for the wonderful staff, parents and children at GOSH. 

From a personal standpoint, I have so much love for the brilliant children in my family and would do whatever it took to keep them healthy. Meanwhile, as a tutor, I am fortunate enough to meet so many inspiring and fantastic children each day. Children are a huge part of our lives, and for that reason, I want to raise funds for the families who rely on GOSH. 

It is essential that they have enough donations to support the life saving work they do that keeps so many families going when they need it most.

I will keep you posted with sweaty selfies, sodden smiles and maps of the runs I complete along the way! 

It's quick, easy and secure to donate - just press the Give Now button! 

GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

Thank you,

Lauren Beaumont

story:
In Loving Memory of Kathleen Susan Mary Batchelor 08.11.1944 - 08.11.2020

It is with deep sadness that I share the news that my beautiful Mum, Sue Batchelor, passed away peacefully on the morning of her 76th birthday on Sunday. 

In these difficult and unprecedented times we will be having a private funeral service, but are very aware that Mum will be so fondly remembered, by so many people who would wish to pay tribute for her kindness, generosity, friendship and humour. We hope to hold a memorial service that more people can attend at a later date, when we are able. Mum had requested donations to her chosen charity, Cancer Research, in lieu of flowers. 

I appreciate that there are people amongst mum’s friends who perhaps do not use the Internet. Should anyone know of somebody who would wish to make a cash donation rather using the online facility, please contact me directly and I will provide an address for cash donations and ensure they are added to the total.

story:
We lost our beloved Pete - husband, father, grandfather, brother, friend - in October to amyloidosis linked to blood cancer.

Whilst there is nothing we can do to bring him back, every penny received helps Cancer Research  UK to develop treatments to manage this devastating disease and hopefully, one day eradicate it altogether. 


We’ll always remember you Pete because there will never be another one to replace you in our hearts, and the love we will always have for you.

story:
I’m wondering this year , if all my wonderful,, amazing and special family and friends that so kindly and thoughtfully send a Christmas card or give a gift could donate to this charity instead.  I love receiving cards and of course presents but feel that this charity is in more of a need than myself. 

I will be donating the cost of the Christmas cards and stamps I would have purchased  to this page , I hope this is ok with everyone. 💕  

If we usually exchange gifts which is amazing ... I’m going to be donating the cost of this to your chosen charity.  I will contact you separately 🎁🎄

I hope this doesn’t sound too bah humbug everyone ... it’s for a number of reasons ... I won’t get to see most of you .., and I wanted to help out and do something worthwhile . It kick started this idea off when I realised it would cost nearly £50 just in stamps and cards and thought how useful this would be to charity 🎅🏻

I want to thank everyone for being so kind, thoughtful  and just so fantastic.  I’ve  missed everyone  so much,  You all mean so much to me and I’m sending a huge hug and all my love to each and everyone of you 💕🤗

Have a fabulous and wonderful Christmas and a hopefully here’s to a cheery getting back together 2021 🎄💕🤗

story:
Well you’ve clicked on this so I hope you are at least half interested in helping me with my quest!

I’m writing this in November 2020, 3 months after losing my strong, healthy, fit dad to that bloody indiscriminating disease. Whilst so many diagnosed people go on to live for many years with it, so many have it erased never to be seen again, I still think it’s important to find the necessary bodies who might one day cure it for good. 

So, I have paid £250 to wander round the Sahara desert and need to raise the rest in sponsorship with everything else going to Cancer Research UK. Please give. Imagine the scenario of me crawling on my hands and knees, towards a mirage, unfunded! 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

In loving memory of ...

Mary Elizabeth (Liz) Benoit (nee Welch)

Victor Louis Benoit

Vivian Benoit

Rosemary Royer

Malcolm Butler

Vicki Wright

Sarah Urquhart

story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page. 

We are raising money in memory of two very special, incredibly missed people. 

My father was truly amazing. The kindest most patient and positive man I have ever met. When he died of prostate cancer at the age of 61 he left a huge hole that will never be filled. 

Our good friend Gillian lost her sister Nicola at the age of 39 leaving behind two beautiful young boys. 

The team at Marie Curie were an incredible support for both of our families and we will always be grateful for the kindness shown to my father and Nicola x

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Our RNLI lifeboats in Ireland protect hundreds of communities through our 24-hour search and rescue service. At Dunmore East there is an all-weather Trent class lifeboat on service, number 14-17 named the
Elizabeth and Ronald. The volunteer crew rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from to be able to save lives.

Irelands unrivalled coasts and inland waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike. But the water remains an
unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.

Keeping our Dunmore East lifeboat maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained. Add to that crew training and kit, and the euros start to add up. During the pandemic we have
still been offering a lifesaving service and are continuing to raise vital
funds,

We haven’t been able to take part in our traditional fundraising this year and rely on donations from the public to continue saving lives. Your donation will help support the running of Dunmore East Lifeboat station and its lifesaving service.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.

Your support is much appreciated.

Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
charity.registrationNumber: 1072612 (England & Wales) and SC043677 (Scotland)
story: Could you go 24 hours without food and be expected to live a normal healthy life? This is a challenge faced daily for approximately 11.3% of the world's population including children. Every minute, more than five child mortalities can be attributed to malnutrition. For those fortunate to survive, malnutrition has detrimental effects on childhood growth and learning abilities. Through FAST 24, Lancaster University students will go without food on 27th November to raise money for UNICEF's emergency food programmes. The United Nation's International Children's Emergency UNICEF is a charity part of the United Nation's Development Group committed to protection of children worldwide. UNICEF provides 80% of the world's life-saving food through its nutrition programmes. With your help, we can help increase access to good nutrition to children worldwide giving them a healthier, happier life.

eventName: No Need November/ Don't Do it December
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

For the remainder of this year I will be giving up unnecessary spending on things that I don't need (from those pretty frocks I spend too much time browsing through online to a supermarket snack that almost lands in my basket) and donating the £ equivalent instead to people who struggle to even get the basics in life, nevermind such excess.

I'm calling this my 'No Need November/Don't Do it December'. 

I would ask that anyone who is thinking of getting me anything for the remainder of the year, including Christmas gifts or cards, please please do the same by donating to this page instead. 

We are fortunate enough to be providing well for our daughter who is turning 2 at the end of November. If anyone wants to get anything for her, cards or presents, please donate here instead as well. I'll show her when she's older and I'm sure she'll appreciate it. 

I don't expect to raise much but anything is better than nothing. Thanks a million if you donate, too.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
charity.registrationNumber: 1072612 (England & Wales) and SC043677 (Scotland)
story:
💙 dear friends! it's that time of the year again 💙 i'm taking the #fast24 challenge for the fourth year in a row along with the unicef team of lancaster uni 💙 (and, sadly, this is my last year taking this challenge as a lancaster student!) on this occasion, we are raising awareness on issues of poverty, hunger and inequality faced by children, as well as fundraising for unicef's emergency programmes, which carry out critical interventions in support of infant and young child survival from countries experiencing humanitarian crises. these interventions include: supporting mothers in safely feeding their babies; providing therapeutic feeding to children suffering from acute malnutrition; sanitising water; delivering essential micronutrients to treat deficiencies.

a few statistics:
820 million people starved in 2019, up from 811 million in 2018 - the third year of increase in a row. due to high costs and low affordability, billions cannot eat nutritiously. the covid-19 pandemic is intensifying the vulnerabilities and inadequacies of global food systems, pushing even more into chronic hunger by the end of 2020.

these statistics are more than mere, cold numbers, as they point to tangible suffering, experienced by real people, people like you and me. my heart is heavy contemplating the immense suffering which i cannot understand, but i know that change can be enacted and help can be given. for this reason, if you have a few pounds to spare, i urge you to donate as much as / if you are comfortable to. 

now, a few words to the brilliant unicef team, as this may be the last time we are crossing paths (in this format!):

thank you!! i haven't been part of a more dedicated team! it still is surreal to me that together we fund-raised ~ £10.000, which made a real difference for disadvantaged children, as we had the opportunity to see. it was a blessing to be part of such a wonderful and impactful project, both as the chief of information officer and as a volunteer. this experience humbled me, guided me in deconstructing my privilege and cemented my hope that one individual can bring forth change. thank you 💙

UNICEF provides 80% of the world's life-saving food through its nutrition programmes. With your help, we can help increase access to good nutrition to children worldwide giving them a healthier, happier life.

charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story:
This year has been a difficult for everyone around the world and we would like to do our bit to help. 

Here at PL, we will be organising a few events that we would love for you to get involved with to help raise funds for "Doctors Without Boarders -MSF"

What MSF stand for:

"Our mission is to provide lifesaving medical care to those most in need. All MSF members agree to honor the following principles: MSF provides assistance to populations in distress, to victims of natural or man-made disasters, and to victims of armed conflict."


What your donations will go towards:

£16
can pay for a surgical tunic, trousers and a pair of sterile reusable gloves.    

£28
can pay for protective plastic goggles for four doctors   

£58
can pay for sterile gloves for 30 medics.   

£110
can pay for five protective suits to keep staff safe.

Please keep an eye on your inbox for any updates.

Many thanks

The Giving Back Team

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. 

Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

With clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene, children are born healthier. They get the chance to go to school and grow up to become adults. Women and men get to earn a living. Whole communities start to thrive. 

It sounds normal and it should be.
